				{
					"type": "thinking_start"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "The user wants me to think about and write a 300-word essay on agentic AI context management. This is a writing/",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "thinking task, not a coding task. Let me just think",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " about this carefully and write a well-crafted essay.\n\nLet me think",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " about what makes a good essay on this topic:\n\n1. **What is agentic AI context management?** - It",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "'s about how AI agents manage their limited context windows while performing complex,",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " multi-step tasks. This includes deciding what information to keep, what to summarize, what to discard, and how",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " to structure working memory.\n",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "\n\n2",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": ". **Key tensions:** There's a fundamental conflict between finite context windows and arbitrarily complex tasks,",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " and I need to balance having enough information for accuracy against the",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " dilution that comes from too much context. Agents face a trade-off between breadth and depth,",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " and they need to actively manage context rather than just passively accumulate it.\n3. **Style considerations:** The user wants",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " something thoughtful and substantive rather than rushed or superficial, and with only 300 words, every sentence has to count",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " and demonstrate real understanding of the topic.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "\n\nNow",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " I'm working through the core argument about context management as the",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " actual bottleneck in agentic AI—the idea that naive accumulation fails because attention",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " dilutes even when information is available, and that effective agents need specific",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " capabilities to handle this constraint.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " that",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "'s the real constraint—context fills up fast, and once",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " it's full, you're either dropping information or paying exponentially for",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " retrieval. The solution isn't a bigger window; it's treating",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " attention as finite and designing around that scarcity through strategic retrieval, aggressive summarization of",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " completed work, and delegating bounded tasks to fresh sub-agents. This mirrors how experienced engineers actually think—they don't memor",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "ize entire systems, they build layered mental models, know where to find things, and ruthlessly focus on what matters for the current problem.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " The agents that will win aren't the ones with the largest context windows,",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " but the ones that use them most deliberately.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " The",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " naive approach of just accumulating everything breaks down fast—",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "a massive context window feels spacious until you're juggling multiple",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " source files, documentation, and test suites, at which point the sheer volume starts",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " degrading performance rather than improving it.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "\n\nEffective context management really",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " comes down to three key capabilities: first, being strategic about what to retrieve by understanding the problem space",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " before diving into search, rather than just grepping blindly; second, ag",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "gressively summarizing completed work into compact representations that capture decisions and outcomes without keeping all the raw details around.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "\n\nThird",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " is delegating bounded subtasks to fresh sub-agents with clean contexts, then pulling back only what matters",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " from their conclusions. What strikes me is how much this mirrors how experienced",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " engineers actually work—they don't memorize entire systems, they build mental models at different levels of abstraction and know",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " exactly where to look things up. The real advantage won't come from agents",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " with massive context windows, but from those that treat attention as the precious resource it actually is and use their windows with",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": " real intentionality.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_delta",
					"text": "",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "thinking_stop"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": "The context window is the bottleneck of agentic AI. An agent that can browse files, run commands, and edit code across a large codebase",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": " operates under a fundamental constraint: it can only attend to a fraction of the information relevant to its task at any moment. Context management -- the discipline of deciding what enters, persists in, and exits the agent's working memory -- is what separates effective agents from expensive autocomplete.\n\nThe",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": " naive approach is accumulation: read everything, keep everything. This fails quickly. A 200,000-token window sounds generous until you've read fifteen source files, three stack traces, and a test suite. The context fills, attention dilutes, and the agent begins making errors not from ignorance but from dist",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": "raction. The problem isn't insufficient information -- it's insufficient curation.\n\nEffective context management requires three capabilities. First, *strategic retrieval*: knowing what to look for before looking, and searching with precision rather than breadth. An agent that greps the entire c",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": "odebase for a keyword is doing less work than one that reads the architecture document first and navigates directly to the relevant module. Second, *aggressive summarization*: compressing completed subtasks into compact representations that preserve decisions and outcomes without retaining raw material. The agent doesn't need the full diff after a ref",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": "actor -- it needs to know what changed and why. Third, *hierarchical delegation*: offloading bounded subtasks to fresh sub-agents with clean contexts, then integrating only their conclusions.\n\nThe deeper insight is that context management mirrors how skilled engineers think. A senior developer doesn't hold an entire system",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": " in their head. They build mental models at varying levels of abstraction, know where to look things up, and ruthlessly prioritize what matters for the current task. The best agentic systems will not be those with the largest context windows, but those that use their windows most deliberately -- treating attention as the scar",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
				{
					"type": "delta",
					"text": "ce resource it is.",
					"messageId": "msg_d28fcc27c001clxwEcmP196OcR"
				},
